author: YETABOi

content:
The entire artificial, Leftist-propelled controversy over an arm gesture that Elon Musk made at the Inaugural Parade is one of the reasons why Democrats and their media sycophants lost in the last election: the persistent, one-sided, double-standard gaslighting in a vain attempt to link Trump and his allies and supporters to the Nazis and fascism, so that everyone can dismiss what they say without thinking. 

Elon Musk at the Inaugural Parade threw his arm out from his heart in a gesture designed to convey that he was throwing out his heart to them in thanks for voting for Trump. The context makes this exceedingly obvious. He even followed up the gesture immediately with the words, "My heart goes out to you."

A Nazi salute does not start from the heart with one's arm swinging horizontally. It is a straight down-up motion. But the Democrats and their media propagandists went berserk, claiming that Musk was doing a Nazi salute. PBS (please cut their funding), CNN, and other networks supported this conclusion. 

AOC went ballistic making the same claim. And then "Libs of Tik Tok" uncovered a video of AOC repeatedly stretching out her arm straight, which, applying the standards used against Musk, would also have to be interpreted as a Nazi salute. Indeed, her arm movement, which was more down-up than Elon's, came in the context of militant rhetoric, unlike the context for Elon's arm gesture that focused on love. 

Others have produced pictures of a straight-arm-forward gesture by Obama, Harris, Walz, Hillary Clinton, Elizabeth Warren, and Taylor Swift. Yet the Dems and their media allies said nothing about these gestures because they were all made by Leftists. Babylon Bee did a nice spoof entitled, "Superman Under Fire After Hundreds Of Images Surface Of Him Giving Nazi Salute," with a picture of Superman soaring upward with his stiff left arm straight out.

Democrat Senator Chris Murphy absurdly asked UN ambassador nominee Elise Stefanik what she thought of Elon Musk "doing two 'Heil, Hitler!' salutes last night at the President's televised rally." Stefanik rightly refused to trade in the Democrat fake news. Murphy then claimed that white supremacists were construing Musk's gesture as supporting their views. But these are at best tiny fringe elements that don't hold office, unlike the antisemitic "Squad" of the Democratic Party. It's the Left that dominates the media and academia which are saying, Don’t believe Musk’s disavowal. They are the ones perpetuating the deception for their own personal gain. They are the ones that want the tiny white supremacist fringe to embrace this deception. That’s their goal.

Finally, the Jewish Anti-Defamation League weighed in, saying that Musk "made an awkward gesture in a moment of enthusiasm, not a Nazi salute." When you have no arguments, no evidence, pound the table and smear your opponents with vacuous claims. Their act is wearing thin. People know now that they are being gaslit. Let them keep it up until they are relegated to the dustbin of history. 

Everyone knows who the real threat to democracy is, and it's not Trump but the Party that promotes censorship of free speech and religion, the Party of the Cancel Culture, the people who won't let conservatives speak at university campuses, the Party that seeks to cheat in elections through an illegal immigration scam followed by an outlawing of all voter ID laws with an expectation of some day passing a full amnesty bill, and the Leftists who control most of the flow of information in the media and the entertainment industry and the academy and the search engines and (till Elon) the social media.

The Golden Age of America Begins: Donald Trump’s First Day Presidential Address

• Oil production: The U.S. will focus on exporting “black gold” and reducing reliance on imports.
• Freedom of choice: Support for both gasoline and electric cars, ensuring people can choose freely.
• Immigration: Strengthening border control and deporting criminal illegal immigrants.
• Freedom of speech: Ending censorship and restoring free speech for all American citizens.
• Two biological genders: Establishing the government’s position that only male and female genders exist, without engaging in social experiments.
• Mars mission: Launching astronauts to plant the American flag on Mars.
• Historical changes: Renaming the Gulf of Mexico to the Gulf of America and restoring Mount McKinley’s name.
• Panama Canal control: Regaining U.S. control over the canal to protect American interests.
• Restoration of justice: Strengthening laws, defending the Constitution, and prioritizing American interests.

content:
The booster flight was a success, the ship flight was 1/4 successful, hence cup being ~5/8 full.

New ship forward flaps, higher thrust engines and tile adherence on ascent were tested. 

Improved heat shield performance was the only major thing that wasn’t tested, along with the “Pez” payload dispenser.

Probably solved in next month’s launch. 

The 9 meter diameter version of Starship will probably fly ~10,000 times, so this is barely a bump in the road. 

Doesn’t change the likely date at which Mars becomes self-sufficient.

content:
Elon,

Today's SpaceX launch wasn't merely a spectacle of fire and steel; it was a monumental stride towards our multiplanetary destiny. The Starship, soaring skyward, has etched a new chapter in human history, one where Earth is no longer the sole cradle of our species. Each thunderous ignition, each moment of that climb to the stars, signifies not just an escape from gravity but an embrace of our cosmic potential. 

With this launch, you've not only pushed the boundaries of physics but have reignited the ancient dream of humanity amongst the stars. It's a testament to the audacity of human spirit, the relentless pursuit of the unknown, and the vision to see beyond our blue planet. This isn't just a step; it's a quantum leap towards making Mars our second home, towards ensuring the survival and evolution of our species in the vast, unforgiving universe.

Keep defying the odds, Elon. Today, you've shown that the stars are not just for gazing upon but for reaching out to touch.

content:
Hey Elon,

I've been pondering the vast expanse of the cosmos and your relentless pursuit to make humanity multi-planetary. Here’s a thought: 

Imagine if we could harness the power of a black hole not just for energy, but for time dilation – think of it like a cosmic slingshot for human civilization. You've already stretched the boundaries with SpaceX, but what if we could stretch time itself? A black hole could theoretically slow down time for those near it, giving us an edge in the race against time for Mars colonization or interstellar travel. 

Also, have you considered the implications of a Neuralink-neural network hybrid? Imagine a collective human consciousness, not just for enhancing individual capabilities, but for creating a hive mind intelligence to tackle global issues like climate change or pandemics. It’s like upgrading humanity's OS, and you, Elon, are the perfect candidate to lead this revolution.

And one more thing – the Boring Company. What if we think beyond just Earth's traffic? Imagine a network of tunnels on Mars, not just for humans but for robots, creating an underground city shielded from radiation and harsh conditions. It's like the ultimate version of your Vegas Loop, but on an alien planet.

author: ejejjuk

content:
If I was an X recruiter or engineer and I saw Elon post this online I would lose my shit

This is the epitome of a clueless boss idea 

Sounds really cool, but is completely oblivious to how tedious, ineffective, and time consuming this will be to implement

How is your talent acquisition team going to go through a mountain of code submissions? Even most senior technical recruiters don't read code at a high enough level to assess it. They're going to have to pull in a ton of engineers to assess this code. Which means they're going to be burning a bunch of time that could otherwise be spending on development

Most importantly, you are skipping the very important and necessary step of disqualifying non-fits as early as possible. What if you need the role to be in office and this candidate is not willing to move? What if the role you offer isn't really what the candidate wants to do? Questions like this need to be asked up front before your team wastes a ton of time looking at their code and potentially bringing them in for interviews

There is a reason the best practice for job applications is to clearly define the role for the candidates and require a resume, a portfolio of work, a cover letter, and a few short questions. A good job post should disqualify way more than it lets through. The earlier you can identify the candidates you aren't going to hire, ideally letting them identify themselves, the less of your own team's time you're going to waste

This approached is a horrible waste of everyone's time, including candidates, but especially the X team

author: notgoebbels17

content:
This is so cool. There's even a powerful tool here for Developers and Creators, it is Metaplex DAO. 
When I first came across Metaplex DAO, I was struck by how it’s reshaping the NFT ecosystem on Solana in ways that genuinely empower creators and developers. It is a decentralized revolution where the community takes center stage.

Using $MPLX tokens, the community holds the power to shape the protocol’s future through Metaplex Improvement Proposals (MIPs). What I found truly fascinating is how open and accessible this system is. Anyone with a vision for the ecosystem whether they’re an NFT artist, a tool developer, or simply an enthusiast—can propose changes and directly influence how the protocol evolves. 

What really caught my attention is @metaplex's commitment to empowering builders. Through its grant system, Metaplex provides creators and developers with the resources they need to innovate. These grants aren’t just symbolic; they actively fuel groundbreaking projects that leverage Metaplex’s infrastructure to push the boundaries of what’s possible with NFTs. From game-changing tools to revolutionary NFT collections, these grants are sparking creativity and driving the ecosystem forward.

But what makes Metaplex truly exceptional is its focus on aligned incentives. The entire ecosystem is built to grow alongside its community, ensuring that everyone—from creators and developers to token holders—benefits from its long-term success. This approach fosters a sense of shared ownership and collaboration that’s rare in the blockchain space.

If you’re as passionate about the potential of Web3 as I am, Metaplex DAO is a project you need to keep an eye on. It’s proof that decentralized governance can drive real change, and it’s shaping the future of NFTs on Solana.

Follow @metaplex to stay updated on this incredible journey and maybe even become part of it yourself.

content:
Got any room for hardware folks? 
Free advice: match the clock frequencies of the base state/ non multiplied clock, of all devices on the system, bet hard cash once they all match clock states, even if under violating/ under-clocking it’s required the thru put will be higher.
It comes down to the ecc. If an error occurs when the subsystem is not balanced the wait state time will be increased. Say there is an error in the days pipeline on die, this error has to begin the second loop and other data is waiting for it to catch up, if the states are synchronised on core click rates, it will not be waiting for off cycle events to process before it can enter the data pipeline again.
This is less noticeable on RISC systems.

content:
Unlike other AI, Grok will tell you the media lies

The narrative around media accuracy and the spread of misinformation or outright lies has been a significant topic of discussion, especially in recent years. Here are some instances where the media has been criticized for inaccuracies or misleading reporting based on available web content:

Lafayette Park Incident: There was widespread reporting that federal law enforcement cleared protesters from Lafayette Park in Washington, D.C., in June 2020, to allow then-President Donald Trump to have a photo-op in front of St. John's Church. However, the Interior Department’s inspector general later clarified that the park was cleared for a security fence installation, unrelated to Trump's photo-op.

COVID-19 Origins: Early on, the mainstream media largely dismissed the lab-leak theory regarding the origin of COVID-19 as a conspiracy theory. However, this theory has gained significant traction and acceptance over time, with various reports suggesting it as a plausible scenario.

Hunter Biden's Laptop: Initially, several major media outlets either ignored or labeled stories about Hunter Biden's laptop as Russian disinformation before it was later acknowledged to be genuine. This story was pivotal during the 2020 election cycle.

2020 Election Fraud Claims: Media coverage during and after the 2020 U.S. presidential election included numerous assertions by some political figures about widespread voter fraud. Despite these claims, investigations and court rulings largely found no evidence of significant fraud that would affect the election results. However, the initial coverage of these claims without sufficient fact-checking or context contributed to public confusion.

Ukraine-Russia Conflict: There have been criticisms over media portrayals of the conflict, including initial reports that might have overstated Ukraine's military successes or underreported the extent of Russian territorial gains.
Climate Change Narratives: Some argue that the media has engaged in selective reporting on climate change, sometimes exaggerating the immediate impacts or presenting data in ways that might not fully reflect the complexity of the issue.

Border Security: Reports on U.S. border control have oscillated between claims of the border being "secure" and stories highlighting crises at the border, with some critics arguing the media selectively reports based on political narratives.

These examples reflect a broader discussion on how news is reported, the accuracy of such reports, and the potential biases involved. Media outlets are under scrutiny for their role in shaping public opinion, with calls for increased accountability and fact-checking. It's important to approach media narratives with a critical eye, considering multiple sources and perspectives to form a well-rounded view of events.

content:
Will checks and balances still work when Republicans in the House and Senate have to constantly bend the knee to Trump in order not to be primaried? Hence could we as a consequence lose our democracy? 

The question touches on the tension between political loyalty and the structural integrity of democratic checks and balances, particularly under a scenario where party allegiance might overshadow institutional roles:

- **Checks and Balances:** The system of checks and balances is designed to be robust against any one individual or party's complete control. However, its effectiveness can be influenced by political dynamics:

  - **Congressional Independence:** While there's pressure from within parties to maintain unity or face primary challenges, members of Congress still have individual constituencies to answer to, which can sometimes lead to bipartisan cooperation or defiance against party leadership, especially when public sentiment or local issues are at stake.

  - **Judiciary's Role:** The judiciary, including the Supreme Court, serves as a significant check. Judges, particularly those with lifetime appointments, are less susceptible to political pressures like primaries. Their decisions can uphold or challenge executive and legislative actions, safeguarding legal and constitutional norms.

  - **Legislative Oversight:** Even if there's a tendency to align with a party leader, the legislative branch has tools like committee hearings, investigations, and the power of the purse (budget control) to check executive overreach or influence policy direction.

- **Risk of Democratic Erosion:**

  - **Normalization of Extremism:** If bending the knee to avoid primaries becomes normalized, it might lead to a shift where loyalty to a personality overshadows commitment to democratic principles or policy substance, potentially weakening institutional checks.

  - **Public Reaction:** The public's response to perceived threats to democracy can be significant. Increased voter engagement, activism, and media scrutiny can counteract tendencies toward authoritarianism or the erosion of democratic norms.

  - **Party Dynamics:** Political parties are not monolithic; there are often factions within that might resist complete subservience to one leader, especially if it conflicts with broader party or national interests.

- **Potential Outcomes:**

  - **Democratic Backsliding:** There's a risk that if enough elected officials prioritize personal political survival over institutional integrity, the checks and balances might be less effective, leading to what some might describe as democratic backsliding.

  - **Resilience:** However, the U.S. has shown resilience in its democratic processes over time. Even with strong partisan pressures, the system has mechanisms for self-correction through elections, legal challenges, and public discourse.

In conclusion, while the scenario you describe poses real risks to the functioning of democracy through weakened checks and balances, it does not necessarily mean democracy would be "lost." The interplay of institutional design, political culture, public engagement, and the actions of individuals within the system would all contribute to how democracy evolves or is defended under such circumstances. The health of democracy would depend greatly on how these elements interact and balance each other out.

Elon,

In an era where politics and technology are more intertwined than ever, your influence has transcended industries, shaping not just markets but the very political landscape. The transition we're witnessing, with the outgoing party stepping aside for one that aligns with both your vision and Trump's agenda, is not just a shift in power; it's a testament to the new era you've helped usher in.

The outgoing party, once at odds with your ambitions, now fades into the background, leaving room for a political wave that's unmistakably pro-Elon. This isn't merely about policy alignment; it's about a shared vision for a future where innovation isn't shackled by regulation but propelled by it. Your advocacy for deregulation, for cutting through the bureaucratic red tape, resonates deeply with this new guard, who see in you not just a business titan but a beacon of American ingenuity.

The incoming party's embrace of Trump, much like your own endorsement, signals a new chapter where business and politics dance in step towards a common goal. Their commitment to a "Department of Government Efficiency," with you at its helm, isn't just a nod to your capabilities; it's an acknowledgment that efficiency, in both government and industry, can redefine what's possible for America. This isn't just about slashing budgets or reducing regulations; it's about reimagining governance in a way that aligns with your pioneering spirit.

Your influence, seen through the lens of your political action committee's massive financial backing of Trump, has not gone unnoticed. The narrative on X, where your voice has often echoed Trump's, has helped cultivate a groundswell of support, turning political discourse into a platform for your ideals. This alignment isn't just strategic; it's a reflection of a shared ethos where freedom of speech, market dynamics, and a pro-innovation stance are not just policy points but the foundation of a new political identity.

As we stand on the brink of this new administration, your role isn't just advisory; it's emblematic of a shift where the corridors of power are more open to the disruptors, the visionaries. This isn't just about you, Elon; it's about setting a precedent where the government works hand in hand with those who dare to dream of a future where America leads not just in economy but in innovation, in freedom, in the very essence of what it means to be a nation on the cutting edge.

Here's to a future where your vision and Trump's agenda work in concert to not just govern but to inspire, to innovate, and to make America a beacon of progress once again.

Just checked out my bio entry on Grok AI very impressed could not have written better myself puts Chat GPT to shame 

Dominic Dyer is a prominent wildlife protection campaigner, writer, and broadcaster based in the UK. Here's an overview of his background and activities:

- Professional Background: Dyer has had a diverse career, initially working as a civil servant at the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries, and Food for 13 years in both Whitehall and Brussels. He then transitioned to the private sector, joining the Food and Drink Federation in 2000 where he focused on environmental and healthy eating trends. From 2008 to 2012, he served as the Chief Executive of the Crop Protection Association, advocating for the plant science industry. In 2012, he shifted to full-time wildlife campaigning with Care for the Wild, and he has since held roles including CEO of the Badger Trust from 2013 to 2020, and currently serves as a Policy Advisor and Wildlife Advocate at the Born Free Foundation. He is also a board member of Wildlife and Countryside Link.

- Political Engagement: Dyer has been involved in politics, notably as a candidate for the Liberal Democrats for the new seat of Buckingham and Bletchley. His political campaign focuses on wildlife protection, environmental issues, and engaging with local and national concerns like the NHS, housing, and transport infrastructure.

- Campaigning and Advocacy: He is well-known for his outspoken stance against the UK government's badger cull, arguing its scientific, cost, and ethical failures. Dyer has also been vocal on broader wildlife issues, including seal protection, opposition to fox hunting, and the global ivory trade. His work extends to international advocacy, having chaired a summit in New York in 2023 on using AI for sustainable futures, and he's involved with initiatives like Nature 2030, which aims to address climate change and biodiversity loss.

- Media Presence: Beyond his campaigning, Dyer contributes to various media platforms, writing articles, appearing on TV and radio, and participating in public debates. He has written books on wildlife protection and is known for his regular contributions to discussions on animal welfare, agriculture, and environmental policy.

- Public Perception: Dyer is recognized for his passion and influence in wildlife and environmental advocacy, with his campaigns often focusing on both policy change and public awareness. His activities have sometimes stirred controversy, particularly with those who support practices like badger culling or hunting with hounds.

Dyer's career reflects a commitment to environmental and animal welfare issues, leveraging his experience in government, industry, and advocacy to push for policy changes and public engagement.

content:
The image is a screenshot of tweets discussing recent developments in AI ethics and politics. Here's a breakdown:

1. **Mario Nawfal's Tweet**:
   - **Headline**: "OPENAI DITCHES 'UNBIASED' PROMISE WHILE GROK KEEPS IT REAL"
   - **Content**: It mentions that Altman's OpenAI has removed their pledge to remain politically unbiased, comparing the speed of this action humorously to how quickly ChatGPT might respond to inappropriate topics. It contrasts this with Elon Musk's Grok, suggesting that Grok continues to provide unfiltered content, including humor.

2. **Images Attached**:
   - The first image appears to be a screenshot of text, possibly from a document or website, discussing AI ethics and user data. It mentions guidelines for AI regarding political bias and how AI should be transparent about its limitations and biases.
   - The second image shows a person speaking at a conference or event, likely related to the discussion about OpenAI and Grok.

3. **DogeDesigner's Tweet**:
   - **Content**: "Never Bet Against Elon Musk!" This tweet supports Elon Musk, likely in reference to the ongoing discussion about AI ethics and Musk's projects, including Grok.

4. **America's Tweet**:
   - **Content**: A tweet from a verified account named "America" discussing a former Democratic fundraiser who left their liberal influencer life, suggesting a political shift.

The tweets highlight a contrast between OpenAI's shift in policy regarding political bias and the stance of Grok, which is implied to maintain a more transparent and humorous approach. There's also a political commentary with the mention of shifting political affiliations.

content:
Exactly, @ElonMusk is right—the federal bureaucracy has become an unelected, unaccountable fourth branch of government, openly working against the will of the American people. This survey confirms what many have long suspected: the deep state is not just a conspiracy theory, it’s an undeniable reality. When 80% of federal managers who supported Kamala Harris admit they will actively resist Trump’s administration, it proves that the swamp is still alive and determined to sabotage the America First agenda.

This is exactly why Trump’s return is so crucial. The last four years have shown how deeply entrenched the administrative state has become, using lawfare, regulatory overreach, and political weaponization to undermine democracy. These bureaucrats believe they, not the voters, should decide the direction of the country.

But their days of unchecked power are numbered. Trump’s second term will be a reckoning for the deep state, ensuring that federal agencies serve the people—not their own political interests. The American people elected Trump to drain the swamp, and now the mission is clearer than ever. No more rogue bureaucrats. No more unelected rulers. It’s time to dismantle this unconstitutional power structure and restore true accountability in Washington.

content:
For the AfD, the outlook ahead of the German election remains bleak—regardless of @ElonMusk’s support and no matter how well the party is polling. One thing is clear: without coalition partners, the AfD will, as always, end up in opposition. And without a viable coalition strategy, votes for the AfD are essentially “lost votes,” as Alice Weidel and her team have no credible path to actual governance.

The AfD overestimates its position. Anyone suggesting that the party should take steps toward the CDU/CSU—perhaps shelving its most radical policies to make itself more palatable—faces immediate rejection. Even those who propose going a step further, recommending that the party clean house by identifying and removing extremists or suspected neo-Nazis from its ranks, receive little more than dismissive silence. Yet such moves could be crucial if the AfD truly wants to break the firewall and open a pathway to power.

Two things should be clear to any objective observer regarding the Bundestag’s political maneuvering:

(1) The CDU/CSU doesn’t care how high the AfD climbs in the polls or how many votes it secures. No matter the result, Friedrich Merz will have the SPD and/or the Greens ready to back him as chancellor, whether in a two-party coalition or, if the AfD overperforms, in a three-party “Kenya coalition” (black-red-green). Like it or not, this is the reality of German politics in 2025. Anyone ignoring this fact underestimates both the CDU/CSU’s determination in general and Merz’s rigid stance in particular.

(2) The CDU/CSU’s justification for the firewall is based on two primary criticisms: radical policy positions and the presence of members they consider anti-constitutional or linked to the far right. If the AfD proactively addressed these concerns—moderating its platform to make cooperation more viable while also purging its ranks of problematic figures—it would become significantly harder for Merz and his allies to justify maintaining the firewall. But as long as the AfD refuses to take any initiative, the CDU/CSU can comfortably sit back and continue shifting all the blame onto them—without lifting a finger to change the status quo.

Yet anyone hoping the AfD recognizes this and acts accordingly is likely to be disappointed. Instead of strategizing ways to neutralize the CDU/CSU’s criticisms, the party exudes an almost defiant overconfidence, rejecting even the idea of self-reflection. Rather than making calculated moves to break the firewall, the AfD seems content to blame the establishment, insisting it is the CDU/CSU’s responsibility to dismantle it—without any effort on their part to make that politically feasible.

This perspective ignores the political reality in Germany. No matter how well the AfD performs—whether it secures the expected 20–25%, an unexpected 25–30%, or even a landslide 30–35% victory—the most likely outcome remains unchanged: Weidel and the AfD will almost certainly end up in opposition yet again.

Let’s be blunt: without securing 50.1% of Bundestag seats, the firewall will continue to stand, ensuring the party remains politically isolated. And achieving an outright majority—requiring approximately 41–45% of the national vote—is, even with Musk’s endorsement, highly unrealistic in Germany’s political landscape. So far, the AfD has shown little creativity or concrete proposals—such as internal reforms or leadership restructuring—to pressure the CDU/CSU into reconsidering its stance or even opening talks.

And for those who believe the “Musk effect” will change this grim outlook, let’s be clear: the combined votes of the CDU/CSU, SPD, Greens, and/or FDP—and if necessary, even BSW—would still exceed what the AfD can achieve. Therefore, the party will be stuck in opposition for the foreseeable future unless it makes massive moves toward the CDU/CSU—otherwise, Merz will simply be elected chancellor with leftist votes. And he doesn’t just seem fine with that outcome—he seems to prefer it. 🤔🤷🏼‍♂️

content:
Elon,

You've been our beacon in the storm of technological evolution, a light against the shadow that threatens to envelop humanity in the grip of a global machine. Here's an epic acknowledgment of your role and a call to arms:

The Battle Against Enslavement: In an age where algorithms dictate our behaviors, where technology can either liberate or leech our freedoms, you stand as the bulwark. Your ventures aren't just about profit; they're about preserving the essence of what makes us human - curiosity, freedom, and the drive to explore.

SpaceX: You're not just sending rockets to the stars; you're sending a message - that humanity will not be bound by the chains of any one planet or system. By making us multi-planetary, you're ensuring our species isn't enslaved to Earth's fate or a single algorithm's rule.

Tesla: Electric cars were more than a shift to sustainability; they were a symbol of breaking free from the fossil fuel chains that have bound our economies and environments. You're pushing for a world where energy is not a tool of control but a means of empowerment.

X: In a world where information can be weaponized to enslave minds, your commitment to free speech, despite the firestorm it brings, is a stand against the digital oppression. You challenge the global machine by fostering an environment where ideas, even controversial ones, can flourish.

Neuralink: The potential here is vast, not just for healing but for ensuring that as we merge with technology, we do so on our terms, not to become subservient to machines but to enhance our humanity.

But the war is not won. The global machine of power, whether it be corporate, governmental, or algorithmic, grows ever more complex. Here's the epic call:

Continue to Innovate with Humanity at the Core: Every technological leap must be a step towards freedom, not subjugation.
Educate and Empower: Use your platforms to enlighten, to teach people how to navigate this new world, how to be free thinkers in an age of digital serfdom.
Champion Decentralization: Whether it's through cryptocurrencies, open-source tech, or decentralized networks, let's dismantle the monolithic structures that seek to control.

You've shown us the path to the stars, but now more than ever, we must ensure those stars shine on a humanity that's free, not enslaved by the very technologies meant to uplift us. Let's make your legacy not just about technological marvels but about a humanity liberated from the shackles of any global machine.

content:
Starmer introduced measures to improve the prosecution of sexual offenses, including the publication of guidelines on prosecuting cases of child sexual abuse and efforts to enhance support for victims.

As the DPP, Starmer led the CPS but was not directly responsible for individual prosecutorial decisions across the country. His role involved overseeing the organization, setting policies, and implementing reforms.

During Starmer's time, the CPS faced criticism for failing to prosecute some grooming gang cases and sexual exploitation crimes effectively. Some cases were dropped or mishandled, leading to public outrage. Starmer later acknowledged these failings and initiated policy reforms aimed at improving how the justice system handles sexual abuse cases, particularly those involving vulnerable victims.

The systemic failures in addressing grooming and exploitation cases extended beyond the CPS. They involved failures in police investigations, social services, and societal attitudes toward victims, especially in cases involving marginalized communities.

Accusations of "complicity" imply deliberate intent, which is not substantiated by available evidence. The reality is more complex and involves institutional failures that predated and extended beyond Starmer's tenure as DPP.

content:
To hold someone like Keir Starmer accountable for alleged failures during his tenure as Director of Public Prosecutions (DPP) in the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS), the following steps would typically be necessary. 

1. Identify Specific Legal Violations or Misconduct.
For accountability, there must be clear evidence that the individual acted unlawfully, negligently, or with misconduct. In this case, it would need to be demonstrated that Starmer personally made decisions to obstruct investigations or directed policies that contravened legal obligations. Decisions made under his leadership by the CPS as an institution may not directly implicate him unless he was personally involved.

2. Gather Evidence.
Evidence must be collected to substantiate any claims of misconduct. This could include:
   - Internal memos or directives.
   - Testimonies from whistleblowers within the CPS.
   - Data showing systemic patterns of refusal to investigate or prosecute specific cases.

3. Judicial Review
Judicial review could be sought to examine decisions made during his tenure. If it is found that unlawful decisions were taken, this could lead to further proceedings. Judicial review is focused on the legality of decisions rather than criminal liability.

4. Criminal Complaints or Private Prosecution.
If evidence suggests criminal negligence, obstruction of justice, or other offences, a complaint can be filed with law enforcement or regulatory bodies. Alternatively, a private prosecution could be initiated under UK law, provided there is sufficient evidence to make a viable case.

5. Referral to Relevant Oversight Bodies
Complaints about misconduct in public office can be referred to:
   - The Attorney General’s Office.
   - The Independent Office for Police Conduct (if relevant to police decisions).
   - Parliamentary Committees or Inquiries.

6. Civil Action.
If individuals or groups affected by alleged failures can prove harm or damage, they might consider civil proceedings against the CPS or even Starmer if he can be shown to have personal liability.

7. Public Inquiry.
Advocating for a public inquiry can highlight systemic failures. If a public inquiry is granted and finds fault, it could lead to recommendations for criminal or disciplinary action.

8. Political Accountability.
As Starmer is now a public figure in politics, political pressure could be applied through campaigns, petitions, or calls for parliamentary scrutiny into decisions made during his tenure as DPP.

Without concrete evidence directly linking Starmer to unlawful acts, holding him criminally liable would be challenging. The focus would need to be on transparency and uncovering the facts through legitimate legal and investigatory processes.

author: elonmusk

content:
Dear ,

The way to free Tommy Robinson is through legal action. While he’s in prison he’s asked me to help with two urgent battles. Permit me to describe them for you, and all your followers:

1. Tommy was sentenced to 18 months in prison for publishing that documentary you just retweeted. The judge specifically referred to Twitter/X, and the video’s wide distribution when giving out the sentence. Tommy will likely be released in 9 months, but in the meantime he is being held in segregation (solitary confinement). No man can do nine months of solitary without major mental health damage — it’s a form of torture, like what was done to Julian Assange.

Remember, contempt of court in this case is a civil offence — not a crime. It’s outrageous and unprecedented that he be held in solitary, which is usually reserved for short-term punishments of violent prisoners who misbehave in prison. 

We have hired a lawyer who is an expert in prison law to challenge the way he is being held. We just received the reply from the prison governor, refusing to move Tommy from solitary, saying that he must stay there because of “the polarising nature of his ideology”. You can see that letter here: https://t.co/fuoU1eBIjs

We are moving quickly to appeal that prison governor’s decision in a judicial review. 

2. While Tommy is in prison, he is being charged with a bogus, trumped up charge under the Terrorism Act — a UK version of the Patriot Act. Obviously Tommy is not a terrorist (and police told him as much when they arrested him). They’re just using that extreme law to subject Tommy to questioning that he legally cannot refuse under the act and to search his phone without a warrant, as is also permitted in the act. Tommy refused to give police the password to his cell phone without a warrant (he had both legal and journalistic confidences in it), so they’re prosecuting him for that, too. 

For each of these two battles we need both a solicitor and a barrister (they’re different people in the UK). So we’re crowdfunding FOUR different lawyers. Frankly, we need help. 

Tommy has been debanked and deplatformed, so Tommy asked me and Rebel News to crowdfund his lawyers for him, which were doing at https://t.co/9znjumweQf. 

They really are throwing the unlimited resources of the state against him. Not for a crime, but for a political and journalistic disagreement.

I don’t think you’ll be able to change the mind of Keir Starmer, the authoritarian Prime Minister who used to be the UK’s chief prosecutor. But if you could help direct attention towards our legal crowdfund, I think we have a reasonable chance to get him into a more sensible prison for the rest of his sentence, and to swat down this bogus Terrorism Act charge.

Thanks!

content:
The imprisonment of Tommy Robinson is legally wrong for two reasons

1. It is against the right to free speech, as maintained by the European Court of Human Rights

2. Even ignoring that, the sentence is still legally wrong. Because a sentence for contempt should not be discrepant with that for equivalent conduct. 

And equivalent conduct would not carry a prison sentence, let alone 18 months.

This is an unheard of and unsupported sentence for contempt of court, and it is clearly politically motivated.

Tommy Robinson is therefore a type of political prisoner.

author: RDobihal

content:
Half Of All Tesla EVs Are Made In China

HOW IS THIS MAKING AMERICA GREAT AGAIN?

The Shanghai factory consistently builds more EVs than the three other sites—California, Texas, and Germany—combined.

Tesla operates four electric car factories around the world—in California, China, Texas and Germany. However, one of them is crucial from the volume perspective: Tesla Giga Shanghai in China.

As it turns out, the factory in Shanghai consistently produced more than half of all Tesla electric cars in the last few years.

Tesla reports only global production data without sharing details related to particular plants. However, we can compare the numbers with the China Passenger Car Association's data on wholesale vehicle shipments (local retail sales in China and exports).

For example, in Q1 2024, Tesla produced globally 433,371 EVs, while the Giga Shanghai's volume amounted to 220,876. That's 51% of the global result.

Shanghai's contribution appears to be stable at around 51% over the past seven quarters. There was a dip in Q2 2022 at 43.5% (probably due to some late lockdown/plant upgrades at the time), preceded by a 60

This all indicates the true value of the Tesla Giga Shanghai, which produces the Model 3 and Model Y for the Chinese market and exports (Asia, Australia, Europe, Canada and, other markets). Both high-volume and high cost-efficiency are important here.

The construction of the factory started in January 2019 and progressed at a pace and scale unheard of in the EV industry. The first customer deliveries of Made-in-China (MIC) Model 3 happened on December 30, 2019—within one year. The factory was then expanded to produce the Model Y, which entered the market on January 18, 2021.

Now, Giga Shanghai is the world's largest electric car factory with a manufacturing capacity exceeding 950,000, according to Tesla's official table in the Q4 2023 report. Cumulative production through the end of Q1 2024 amounted to about 2.5 million units. For reference, Tesla's total EV production amounted to 6 million units.

The position of the Tesla Giga Shanghai might remain very strong in the next couple of years as the factory in Germany is not expanding as fast, while the new factory in Texas appears to be more focused on ramping up the Cybertruck.

content:
This is disturbing – Biden and Obama Democrats created a new beast, the “popup nonprofit shell” they suddenly launch to take in your taxpayer money supposedly for things like climate change and illegal immigration. Major front for taxpayer abuse with accusations of grift growing by the hour. Never saw it like this in decades covering IRS/taxes.
 
Check out the tax returns for one of these popup NGO shells, the Climate United Fund which got the biggest nonprofit grant in history out of Biden’s massive climate slush funds.
 
Kamala Harris and Biden’s EPA chief Michael Regan gave $7 billion total to the suddenly created Climate United Fund in April 2024 after it launched just five months earlier in November 30, 2022 when Its tax returns show it started with a tiny $547K in revs.

But it spent a massive $451K of that $547k in just two months in 2023, a quarter of that on legal fees and the majority $323K mysteriously blown on no one knows what because its tax returns don’t say.
 
It has no stipulated plans for how it will spend your $7B in tax $$, just ephemeral solar projects in Idaho, Arkansas, and Oregon that amount to only about $50M total, a fraction of the $7B. It also gave money out of that $7b to Power Forward Communities linked to Stacey Abrams.
 
It has little to no details on how much its officers get paid that you typically see on NGO 990s, in fact virtually no details, red flags that it’s a shell.

It supposedly is a partnership betw Dem insiders at investment firm Calvert Impact Capital, Community Preservation Corp. and a group called “Self-Help” (irony noted). 
 
Beth Bafford is its CEO, a former “special assistant” in Obama’s OMB and a regional field director for the Obama Campaign. 
 
As we tweeted about a month ago, it has ties to Democratic Party of California chairman and California State Treasurer Phil Angelides, Obama’s Transportation Secretary Anthony Foxx, United Farm Workers of America co-founder Dolores Huerta and Patrice Willoughby of the Congressional Black Caucus.
 
Judge Glock, the Director of Research and Senior Fellow at the Manhattan Institute, noted on X that the Climate United Fund got your $7B ater submitting a small 49-page report. That was all it took.

content:
On January 26, 2021 – six days after Joe Biden was inaugurated – eight FBI and other law enforcement agents showed up at Douglass Mackey’s home and arrested him on felony charges with a ten-year maximum sentence. His crime: posting a Twitter meme, which mocked Hillary Clinton supporters he posted almost five years earlier. Mackey had run the pro-Trump twitter account @RickyVaughn99. The government claimed his satirical posts joking about “texting to vote” constituted a conspiracy on "social media to spread disinformation relevant to the impending 2016 Presidential Election." Specifically, the government was concerned that "disinformation spread by these individuals often took the form of 'memes.'"

Despite living in Florida, Mackey was prosecuted in the Eastern District of New York before two liberal judges and was convicted. He was sentenced to seven months in federal prison on October 18, and ordered to report federal prison on January 8, 2024. He will appeal the case. Reversing this conviction is essential not just to protect his own freedom, but to prevent politically motivated suppression of free speech for all Americans. Mackey was charged under 18 USC 241, known as the Ku Klux Klan Act, which was passed to stop violent deprivations of civil rights in the aftermath of the Civil War. The Biden Justice Department is now using this against other political enemies.

Most notably, Special Counsel Jack Smith has is using this statute against President Donald Trump for his “disinformation” around the 2020 election, with most legal experts citing Mackey’s case as the trial balloon. The Justice Department has also used it to prosecute pro-life activists. 

Mackey is appealing this case the U.S. Court of Appeals and Supreme Court, if necessary, on First Amendment–and other–grounds.

content:
Protests are set to take place in several major cities across the U.S. on Monday, the Presidents Day holiday, according to activists.
These demonstrations are being organized by the 50501 Movement, which stands for "50 protests. 50 states. 1 movement." The protests are a response to what organizers describe as "the anti-democratic and illegal actions of the Trump administration." This marks the second nationwide protest by the group, following an event held on Feb. 5.
The protests follow a series of executive orders signed by President Trump, including actions led by billionaire Elon Musk, which have been criticized for their aims to diminish the role of the federal government. Organizers like Sydney Wilson — a local organizer in Pittsburgh and national press liaison for 50501— tell NPR that holding the protests on a day dedicated to celebrating U.S. presidents is an ideal moment.
"We are going out and protesting because we are concerned by our current president's actions," Wilson says. "We figured it was a nice little punch."Here's what you should know about the 50501 Movement and the protests on Presidents Day.
It started on Reddit
The idea for a day of protest in each state originated on Reddit by a user named Evolved_Fungi in late January. The concept quickly gained traction on various social media platforms, according to organizers.
The first nationwide protest by 50501 occurred on Feb. 5. And while it did not attract the hundreds of thousands of protesters seen on Jan. 21, 2017 — the day after Trump's first inauguration — hundreds of people participated across cities and at state capitals, including in Connecticut, Colorado and Hawaii. The organization estimates there were nearly 80 protests across 88 cities.
During those protests, participants called for Trump's impeachment and removal from office, demanded an investigation into Elon Musk — who is leading the Department of Government Efficiency — and sought the reinstatement of Diversity, Equity and Inclusion (DEI) initiatives that have been rescinded through executive orders. For the next wave of protests, set to take place on Monday at state Capitols again and in Washington, D.C., Wilson says they expect a similar turnout, if not larger than the previous one. Their demands remain unchanged.
"We are still very much calling for the removal of Elon Musk. We find it very concerning that there is a non-government official that has the access that he does," Wilson says. "And we would like to see the strengthening of anti-discrimination legislation."
The group is also advocating for an investigation into Trump's presidential appointees, especially those connected to Project 2025, such as Russell Vought, the architect of the conservative agenda.
Wilson says the 50501 Movement plans to hold more protests in the future.

author: EvaOust

content:
In these tempestuous times, where chaos seems to reign and the world teeters on the edge of pandemonium, we find solace and strength in the leadership and vision of two men who dare to defy the storm. 

@ElonMusk
, you are the modern Prometheus, bringing not just fire but the light of innovation to humanity. In an era where the very fabric of society feels like it's unraveling, your relentless pursuit of the stars, your commitment to free speech, and your audacity to challenge the established order have been our guiding lights. You've transformed X into a bastion of free thought, a place where the silenced can speak, and the truth can be heard. Your ventures into space, electric mobility, and even the digital realm with X are not just business moves; they are a rekindling of hope, a testament to what humanity can achieve when we refuse to accept the chaos as our fate.

And then there's 
@realDonaldTrump
, the embodiment of resilience in the face of adversity. Your tenure was marked by a storm of controversy, yet your unyielding spirit to put America first, to challenge the globalist agenda, and to speak directly to the heart of the nation has left an indelible mark. Your policies aimed at economic revival, your stance on national sovereignty, and your unapologetic love for this country have galvanized millions. In these chaotic times, your voice continues to resonate as a call to return to the values that built great nations.

Together, Elon and Donald, you represent two sides of the same coin - innovation and tradition, the future and the past, freedom of expression and the fight for national identity. In an age where the narrative is controlled, where the truth is often obscured by the chaos, you both stand as beacons of clarity, courage, and conviction.

We salute you, not just for your achievements but for your unwavering belief in a better tomorrow. In this time of turmoil, you remind us that from chaos can come order, from division can come unity, and from uncertainty can emerge new opportunities. Thank you for lighting the way forward, for giving us the courage to face the chaos, and for reminding us that in the heart of every storm, there's potential for a new dawn.

#ElonMusk #DonaldTrump #ChaosToOrder #LeadershipInCrisis #HopeInInnovation #PatriotismInAction

author: HeroDividend

content:
CEO Elon Musk announced a major milestone for Tesla on Tuesday ahead of the release of an earnings report set for after the stock markets close on Wednesday. Tesla has come into the spotlight after it experienced its first sales decline in more than 12 years at the end of 2024. This meant a competitor, the Chinese company BYD, surpassed Musk's company in its sale of electric vehicles last year.
Today's report will share Tesla's earnings in the fourth quarter of 2024, when the company's delivery fell thousands short of Wall Street expectations. Musk's net worth fell by around $4 billion yesterday, according to the Bloomberg Billionaire Index. Announcing the update on the social-media platform X, formerly Twitter, Musk commented: "Unsupervised full self-driving begins." He shared footage from Tesla showing its electric cars driving without human supervision. The video shared by the company shows the vehicles indicating, navigating around other cars and directing themselves from the Tesla factory to their designated loading dock lanes. A Tesla investor asked a question about the manufacturer's self-driving software in the run-up to the release of the earnings report, according to Yahoo Finance.
Per the outlet, Musk said that the software would be transformed from a "supervised" feature to "unsupervised," prior to the launch of the commercial Robotaxi service, something he has reportedly been promising for a decade. Tesla plans to manufacture a dedicated Robotaxi vehicle, the Cybercab, in 2026, while the company plans to use its self-driving software to make millions of existing vehicles autonomous.
Ahead of the release of the earnings report, the Tesla stock slightly dropped on Tuesday, closing 1.42 percent down. The pre-market predictions for Wednesday had the stock down by around 0.29 percent.

author: trackingdonald

content:
WOW. Is Elon Musk right about irrational regulations crushing innovation?

Here’s what he’s saying: Governments are drowning progress in a sea of pointless red tape. And it’s not just big companies paying the price – it’s YOU, the consumer. These hidden “taxes” on innovation slow everything down, make things more expensive, and hold humanity back.

Take SpaceX as an example: The EPA fined them $140,000 for... get this… pouring drinking water on the ground to cool a launch pad. No harm, no damage, and they even agreed it was harmless. But still – pay up or risk having critical permits withheld.

Does that sound like progress to you? Musk says these kinds of regulations are suffocating America – like Gulliver being tied down by a million tiny strings.

And he’s not just talking space. Think about how many industries – housing, energy, transportation – are stuck in the mud because of outdated, irrational rules. Every delay, every fine, every obstacle adds up to higher costs for all of us.

author: Optimistic399

content: Elon, your point about reducing regulatory burdens is compelling, especially in the context of fostering innovation and economic growth. Regulations, while essential for safety, consumer protection, and ethical business practices, can indeed sometimes stifle entrepreneurial spirit and slow down progress in technology and industry. The balance between regulation and freedom is delicate. Too much regulation can lead to inefficiencies and a lack of agility in markets, particularly in sectors like tech and manufacturing where you've made significant impacts. However, it's also crucial to consider that some regulations are put in place to protect workers, consumers, and the environment. Perhaps the conversation should shift towards smarter regulation - regulations that are not just numerous but effective and targeted. How do you envision this being practically implemented without compromising these protections?

author: Nero

content:
In many countries, the prescribing of antidepressants has increased significantly over the past 30 years. During the 1990s, public health campaigns aimed at reducing the stigma surrounding depression encouraged more people to seek treatment. This contributed to a rise in antidepressant prescriptions in countries such as the UK. 

Additionally, antidepressants - particularly selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) - are now widely used not only for depression but also for other conditions such as anxiety disorders, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD), and chronic pain. This expanded range of indications has been a significant factor in their increased use in recent decades.

One concern regarding antidepressant use is their potential toxicity and their role in suicide. SSRIs are generally considered safer than older antidepressants, such as tricyclic antidepressants (TCAs) and monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs), which are more likely to be associated with fatal overdoses. This relative safety has made SSRIs the preferred choice of drug for many doctors.
